NAME
	intervalcli - Timer, Alarm, Stopwatch, Clock tool

SYNOPSIS
	intervalcli --[long options] -[options] [single time value]

DESCRIPTION
	The program can run a timer of specified time.
	The program can set an alarm for a specified time.
	The program can start a stopwatch from a specified time or from zero.

	MODES:
		Timer
		Alarm
		Stopwatch
		Print

	Different options or long options may be required depending on the mode.

	--help
		Return help message showing commands and options

	--version
		Return program version information

	--config
		Launch config editor of program config file (requires root)

	--repair
		Delete and regenerate program config file (requires root)

	--codes
		Return a list of program exit codes

	--print
		Returns system time according to settings in config file. Options can be added to manipulate output as shown:
			--[time zone abreviation]
				Converts returned time to specified time zone. Ex: PDT, EST, PST...
			-[field]
				Only returns specified field. field may be 's' for second, 'm' for minute, or 'h' for hour
			[time format]
				Converts returned time to 12 hour or 24 hour format. This option is not preceded by a '-'.
				This option can either be entered as '12' or '24'.

	-t
		Run interval in timer mode

	-a
		Run interval in alarm mode

	-w
		Run interval in stopwatch mode

	-m
		If used with '--print':
			Returns minute value only
		Otherwise:
			Sets time value to minute value

	-s
		If used with '--print':
			Returns second value only
		Otherwise:
			Sets time value to second value

	-h
		If used with '--print':
			Returns hour value only
		Otherwise:
			Sets time value to hour value

	-DM
		Displays fields up to the minute field, then trunkates the rest.

	-DH
		Displays fields up to the hour field, then trunkates the rest.

	-q
		Sets interval to quiet output mode. Only outputs 'Timer running...'

	-FQ
		Sets interval to full quiet mode where there is not output to console

	-v
		Sets interval to verbose mode.

	[single time value]
		At the end of a command, a positive integer can be entered as the timer or stopwatch time.
		This value's repreasentation is determined by '-h', '-m', '-s' options.

USAGE EXAMPLES
	Set a timer for 30 minutes:
		intervalcli -t -m 30

	Print time in 12H format:
		intervalcli --print 12

	Print time hour value in 12H format for PDT timezone:
		intervalcli --print -h --PDT 12

	Start stopwatch at 1 hour:
		intervalcli -w -h 1

	Start alarm mode with verbose:
		intervalcli -a -v

